WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.948 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.948 --> 00:00:04.383 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.383 --> 00:00:07.305 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.305 --> 00:00:10.720 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:17.830 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK, so
last time we talked about,

00:00:17.830 --> 00:00:19.580 align:middle line:84%
in particular, we
talked about two things.

00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:24.580 align:middle line:84%
We talked about the Cauchy
Convergence Theorem.

00:00:24.580 --> 00:00:30.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:32.840 align:middle line:84%
So the Cauchy
Convergence Theorem

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:47.220 align:middle line:84%
says that any Cauchy
sequence is convergent.

00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:51.280 align:middle line:90%


00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:56.200 align:middle line:84%
So this is one thing we talked
quite a bit about last time.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:57.600 align:middle line:90%
And we proved it.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:00.300 align:middle line:84%
But we proved it
assuming another theorem,

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:12.420 align:middle line:84%
so we showed it, the proof used
the Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem.

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:21.040 align:middle line:90%


00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:26.160 align:middle line:84%
Now, the Bolzano-Weierstrass
Theorem--

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:27.900 align:middle line:90%
so that's the following--

00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:39.600 align:middle line:90%


00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:42.880 align:middle line:84%
so this is the
following theorem.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:44.900 align:middle line:90%
Let's say that any bounded--

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:49.600 align:middle line:90%


00:01:49.600 --> 00:02:01.460 align:middle line:84%
sorry, any bounded sequence, an,
has a convergent subsequence.

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:12.920 align:middle line:90%


00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:15.320 align:middle line:90%
And let's call it ank.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:18.080 align:middle line:84%
That was the
Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:21.620 align:middle line:84%
So using this-- remember, the
Cauchy Convergence Theorem,

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:25.080 align:middle line:84%
the proof then went like this,
that if you take a Cauchy

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:29.560 align:middle line:84%
sequence, then it was easy
to prove that it was bounded,

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:33.320 align:middle line:84%
then you use the
Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:36.500 align:middle line:84%
to say that now the
sequence is bounded--

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.000 align:middle line:84%
it's a Cauchy sequence--
the sequence is bounded,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000 align:middle line:84%
so it has a convergent
subsequence, and the limit--

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.320 align:middle line:84%
you would then want to prove
that the limit is actually

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:48.920 align:middle line:90%
a limit for the whole sequence.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:52.640 align:middle line:90%
That's what we did, right?

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:55.540 align:middle line:84%
But we didn't prove the
Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem.

00:02:55.540 --> 00:03:01.760 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to prove
it now, so proof

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:03.826 align:middle line:90%
of the Bolzano-Weierstrass.

00:03:03.826 --> 00:03:13.560 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:17.520 align:middle line:84%
So let me try to
explain the idea.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:24.240 align:middle line:84%
So you have a sequence,
a n, and a n is bounded.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.320 align:middle line:84%
Let's just say it
doesn't matter.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:31.480 align:middle line:84%
But let's say that a n lie
in the interval from 0 to 1.

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:34.320 align:middle line:84%
It could be any other
bounded interval.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.520 align:middle line:90%
But let's just say 0 to 1.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:44.840 align:middle line:84%
Then the idea is that you
want to prove that an--

00:03:44.840 --> 00:04:04.570 align:middle line:84%
so the idea is that we want
to find a subsequence, ank,

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:22.490 align:middle line:84%
and two other sequences,
a-- sorry, bk and ck.

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:24.410 align:middle line:84%
And these two other
sequences have

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:31.450 align:middle line:84%
the property that if
you have here ank, then

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:35.350 align:middle line:90%
the b's lie below--

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:38.050 align:middle line:90%
they lie below the a and k.

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:42.150 align:middle line:90%
And the c's lies above it.

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:44.730 align:middle line:90%


00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:50.370 align:middle line:84%
So the sequence, the
subsequence that we will find

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:55.750 align:middle line:84%
is going to be squeezed
between two other sequences.

00:04:55.750 --> 00:05:06.910 align:middle line:84%
So a and k is squeezed
between two other sequences.

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:12.850 align:middle line:90%


00:05:12.850 --> 00:05:15.450 align:middle line:84%
And the thing about
the other sequences

00:05:15.450 --> 00:05:19.270 align:middle line:90%
is that they are much nicer.

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:21.370 align:middle line:90%
So why are they much nicer?

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:28.130 align:middle line:84%
The bk's are
monotone increasing.

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:33.310 align:middle line:84%
And the ck are
monotone decreasing.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:35.890 align:middle line:90%


00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:40.270 align:middle line:90%
So you have that.

00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:47.090 align:middle line:84%
So the picture is that
the b's are always

00:05:47.090 --> 00:05:48.970 align:middle line:90%
moving in this direction.

00:05:48.970 --> 00:05:50.310 align:middle line:90%
The c's here.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:51.930 align:middle line:90%
This is the b's.

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:57.410 align:middle line:84%
As k gets larger, they're
moving to the right.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.810 align:middle line:84%
And the ck's are
moving to the left.

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:06.850 align:middle line:84%
And these guys, a
and k, they will

00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:08.770 align:middle line:90%
be squeezed between these two.

00:06:08.770 --> 00:06:15.170 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at a
later one, so this is like one.

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:22.290 align:middle line:84%
And now imagine that you take
a later in the subsequence--

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:26.530 align:middle line:84%
sorry, let me indicate
it here, an, say,

00:06:26.530 --> 00:06:33.130 align:middle line:84%
l, and l is now further
out in the subsequence--

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:42.330 align:middle line:84%
then this is going to be
lying between bl and cl.

00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:48.410 align:middle line:84%
But these here, these here
will lie-- the bl, because it's

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:50.370 align:middle line:84%
further out in
subsequence, it will

00:06:50.370 --> 00:06:54.210 align:middle line:84%
lie to the right of
the-- so here will be bk.

00:06:54.210 --> 00:06:57.090 align:middle line:84%
It would be bk would
be to the left,

00:06:57.090 --> 00:07:01.850 align:middle line:84%
and ck would be to the
right of this, right?

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:05.030 align:middle line:84%
So you see that these
here are coming together.

00:07:05.030 --> 00:07:07.610 align:middle line:84%
They're coming
together like this.

00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:12.530 align:middle line:84%
And the a, the
subsequence is going

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:15.850 align:middle line:84%
to be squeezed in smaller
and smaller interval.

00:07:15.850 --> 00:07:18.730 align:middle line:84%
And that's going to
force it to converge.

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:24.810 align:middle line:84%
And the point here is that
because this here is increasing,

00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:28.410 align:middle line:84%
and they always lie between
the ones that go below,

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:32.450 align:middle line:84%
this automatically means
that the bk's will always

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:37.530 align:middle line:90%
be less than the first c.

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:46.970 align:middle line:84%
And these ck's will always
be bigger than the first b.

00:07:46.970 --> 00:07:51.730 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a monotone
sequence that go up,

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:54.650 align:middle line:84%
but it's bounded,
so it has a limit.

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:59.770 align:middle line:84%
So bk is converging
to something.

00:07:59.770 --> 00:08:03.010 align:middle line:84%
The ck's are going
down, but they're

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:05.090 align:middle line:90%
uniformly bounded from below.

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:09.490 align:middle line:84%
So they will also be
converging, right?

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:12.210 align:middle line:84%
But now they're coming
closer together.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:14.310 align:middle line:84%
They're coming closer
and closer together.

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:15.590 align:middle line:90%
This is converging to that.

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:17.210 align:middle line:90%
And this is converging to this.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:22.630 align:middle line:84%
So that's going to imply
that b is equal to c.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:23.390 align:middle line:90%
That's the idea.

00:08:23.390 --> 00:08:24.530 align:middle line:90%
Yes, sir?

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:26.750 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do they need
to be strictly monotonic?

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:34.650 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: They
will have-- sorry,

00:08:34.650 --> 00:08:40.809 align:middle line:84%
the bk will be less
or equal to bk plus 1.

00:08:40.809 --> 00:08:51.250 align:middle line:84%
And the ck will be bigger
or equal to ck plus 1.

00:08:51.250 --> 00:08:52.430 align:middle line:90%
So it's not strict.

00:08:52.430 --> 00:08:54.870 align:middle line:90%
It's inequality, like this.

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:57.510 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] you had a
constant [INAUDIBLE] constant?

00:08:57.510 --> 00:08:58.927 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
Yeah that's right.

00:08:58.927 --> 00:09:02.730 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is also
that they are going to,

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:04.250 align:middle line:90%
that the difference--

00:09:04.250 --> 00:09:10.610 align:middle line:90%
so the ck is lying above the bk.

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:12.370 align:middle line:90%
So this here is positive.

00:09:12.370 --> 00:09:17.990 align:middle line:84%
And we will prove that
this here is bounded by 2.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:21.170 align:middle line:84%
It was actually
going to be equal to.

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:27.530 align:middle line:84%
We would actually prove that
this here is equal to 1 minus,

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:28.730 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:31.010 align:middle line:90%
And you see this here goes to 0.

00:09:31.010 --> 00:09:35.250 align:middle line:84%
So you're right that if
they didn't come together,

00:09:35.250 --> 00:09:37.310 align:middle line:90%
we couldn't conclude things.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:38.670 align:middle line:90%
But they will come together.

00:09:38.670 --> 00:09:40.050 align:middle line:90%
This I will guarantee.

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:41.350 align:middle line:90%
So how do we do this?

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:42.070 align:middle line:90%
That's the idea.

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:45.530 align:middle line:90%
How do we do this?

00:09:45.530 --> 00:09:51.840 align:middle line:84%
Well, and again, I'm
just doing 0 to 1.

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:55.030 align:middle line:84%
But the same argument works
for any other interval.

00:09:55.030 --> 00:09:58.840 align:middle line:90%


00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:02.420 align:middle line:84%
It will look simpler
if I do it from 0 to 1,

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:06.780 align:middle line:84%
but it's not-- there's nothing
essential I'm using about it.

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:13.380 align:middle line:84%
So here is your starting
interval from 0 to 1.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:16.060 align:middle line:84%
We want to construct
a subsequence.

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:20.500 align:middle line:84%
And not only do we want to
construct a subsequence,

00:10:20.500 --> 00:10:24.940 align:middle line:84%
but we also want to construct
the sequence bk and the sequence

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:27.180 align:middle line:90%
ck, right?

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:34.300 align:middle line:90%
So let me define b1.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:37.540 align:middle line:90%
b1 is just going to be 0.

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:41.780 align:middle line:90%
c1 is going to be 1.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:49.620 align:middle line:84%
And then an1-- that's the
subsequence, the first element

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:50.780 align:middle line:90%
is subsequence.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:54.260 align:middle line:84%
I just take it to be the
first element in sequence.

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:58.340 align:middle line:84%
So now of course,
we have trivially

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:02.900 align:middle line:84%
that we have that
b1, which is 0,

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:05.460 align:middle line:84%
this is less than
or equal to a1,

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:09.900 align:middle line:84%
because it lie in this interval,
less than or equal to c1,

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:11.060 align:middle line:90%
which is 1.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:18.360 align:middle line:84%
Now, then you divide it
into two intervals here.

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So the second step is that you
take the interval from 0 to 1.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.500 align:middle line:90%
You divide it into two halves.

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:35.860 align:middle line:84%
So you have between 0
and 1/2 and 1/2 and 1.

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:39.900 align:middle line:84%
The whole sequence
lie in this interval.

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:41.700 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
there are either

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:46.380 align:middle line:84%
infinitely many here or
infinitely many there, right?

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:51.980 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that infinitely many
of the a n lie in this interval.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:56.920 align:middle line:90%
So then we're going to forward.

00:11:56.920 --> 00:11:59.820 align:middle line:84%
We were going to just
focus on this interval

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:01.780 align:middle line:90%
and on subintervals of this.

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:08.100 align:middle line:90%
So we have defined a1.

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:09.860 align:middle line:90%
Now we want to define--

00:12:09.860 --> 00:12:12.480 align:middle line:90%
and b1 and c1.

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:29.140 align:middle line:84%
So now I can assume that
infinitely many a n's lie

00:12:29.140 --> 00:12:31.380 align:middle line:90%
in this interval, right?

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:36.620 align:middle line:90%
So then we take an2--

00:12:36.620 --> 00:12:39.580 align:middle line:84%
the second element
in a subsequence,

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:43.660 align:middle line:84%
we let it be the next
element after a1 that

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:45.940 align:middle line:90%
is in this smaller interval.

00:12:45.940 --> 00:13:04.340 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the second
element in the original sequence

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:14.740 align:middle line:84%
that lies in the
interval from 0 to 1/2.

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:16.340 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:18.400 align:middle line:90%
That's an2, right?

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:20.480 align:middle line:90%
We don't want to have a1 again.

00:13:20.480 --> 00:13:23.030 align:middle line:84%
We need another element,
because otherwise it's

00:13:23.030 --> 00:13:24.280 align:middle line:90%
not going to be a subsequence.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:27.222 align:middle line:90%
You can't pick the A1.

00:13:27.222 --> 00:13:28.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it could
be the same value.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:32.580 align:middle line:84%
But it will have to come
from a different subscript.

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:38.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, b2 is then just going
to be the left endpoint

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:40.460 align:middle line:90%
of this interval.

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:42.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is again 0.

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:47.620 align:middle line:84%
And c2 is going to be the right
endpoint of this interval we're

00:13:47.620 --> 00:13:48.940 align:middle line:90%
now focusing on.

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:49.640 align:middle line:90%
So that's 1/2.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:53.140 align:middle line:90%


00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:58.000 align:middle line:90%
Now, so now to the next--

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:05.420 align:middle line:84%
so now, how do we construct the
third element in the subsequence

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:11.620 align:middle line:84%
and the corresponding
b's and c's?

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:15.820 align:middle line:84%
The thing is that-- and here you
have to be a little bit careful,

00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:21.820 align:middle line:84%
because now, we assumed
that there was infinitely

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:24.460 align:middle line:84%
many elements in
the sequence that

00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:26.980 align:middle line:90%
lie in this smaller interval.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:29.520 align:middle line:84%
You are going to only--
from here on out,

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:33.540 align:middle line:84%
you're going to only look
at those infinitely many.

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:35.900 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to
care about, you know,

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:38.160 align:middle line:84%
so this may be the
fifth, the seventh,

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:40.840 align:middle line:84%
the 15th element in
the original sequence.

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:44.220 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to worry
about what lies here.

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:48.980 align:middle line:84%
And so now you divide this
one here into two halves.

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:54.860 align:middle line:84%
This interval between 0 and
1/2, you divide it into halves.

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:58.960 align:middle line:84%
And so now, imagine you
have then the picture here.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:00.460 align:middle line:90%
Here you have 0.

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:04.900 align:middle line:90%
Here you have a 1/2.

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:08.880 align:middle line:84%
And then you divide it into
this integral from 0 to 1/2.

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:14.980 align:middle line:84%
You divide it into two
equally large intervals.

00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:22.740 align:middle line:84%
So now, we're just focusing
on the infinitely many

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:25.980 align:middle line:84%
of the original
sequences that lie here.

00:15:25.980 --> 00:15:29.500 align:middle line:84%
But of those infinitely
many, either infinitely many

00:15:29.500 --> 00:15:33.380 align:middle line:84%
lie here, or infinitely
many lie there.

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:37.160 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that there's only
finitely many here, say,

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.310 align:middle line:84%
but there are
infinitely many here.

00:15:40.310 --> 00:15:43.270 align:middle line:84%
So if there's infinitely
many in this interval

00:15:43.270 --> 00:15:46.990 align:middle line:84%
here, then from here
on out, you would only

00:15:46.990 --> 00:15:49.230 align:middle line:90%
focus on those infinitely many.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:52.990 align:middle line:90%
And the next element would be--

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:56.390 align:middle line:84%
we know that by the
next element would

00:15:56.390 --> 00:16:00.630 align:middle line:84%
be the next element
after the one

00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:05.790 align:middle line:84%
you pick to be the second
element in the subsequence that

00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:09.870 align:middle line:90%
would lie in this subsequence.

00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:15.670 align:middle line:84%
So we define a3 is
now the next element.

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:25.630 align:middle line:84%
So an3, this is now this element
that lies in this interval here.

00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:33.830 align:middle line:84%
And then b3 is then
going to be 1 over 4.

00:16:33.830 --> 00:16:41.430 align:middle line:84%
And b-- sorry, and c3 is going
to be the right endpoint of this

00:16:41.430 --> 00:16:44.310 align:middle line:90%
interval, 1/4--

00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:46.550 align:middle line:90%
1/2, sorry.

00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:52.110 align:middle line:90%
And then you continue.

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:54.050 align:middle line:90%
Then you continue this way.

00:16:54.050 --> 00:16:56.650 align:middle line:84%
So let me just make sure
that it's totally clear.

00:16:56.650 --> 00:17:00.310 align:middle line:84%
Let me just go
over how we did it,

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:07.310 align:middle line:84%
so just because I want to be
careful that once you-- so we

00:17:07.310 --> 00:17:10.030 align:middle line:84%
started with the
interval from 0 to 1.

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:13.190 align:middle line:84%
The first element you just
pick in the subsequence,

00:17:13.190 --> 00:17:16.710 align:middle line:84%
that was just the first element
in the original sequence.

00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:22.109 align:middle line:84%
And the b1 was just the left
endpoint here, so that was 0.

00:17:22.109 --> 00:17:23.930 align:middle line:90%
c1 was the right endpoint.

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:26.670 align:middle line:90%
That was 1.

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:29.270 align:middle line:90%
Now you divide it into 2.

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:31.590 align:middle line:90%
And one of the two halves--

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:33.790 align:middle line:84%
potentially, of course,
both of the two halves

00:17:33.790 --> 00:17:35.910 align:middle line:84%
could have infinitely
many elements

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:37.910 align:middle line:90%
in the original sequence.

00:17:37.910 --> 00:17:41.390 align:middle line:84%
You just focus on
one of the two halves

00:17:41.390 --> 00:17:43.710 align:middle line:90%
that have infinite elements.

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:47.950 align:middle line:84%
If they're both, fine, but
you just take one of them.

00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:50.310 align:middle line:84%
And so from here
on out, we're just

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:54.070 align:middle line:84%
going to focus on
those infinitely many.

00:17:54.070 --> 00:17:57.510 align:middle line:84%
And then you're going
to pick the next one

00:17:57.510 --> 00:18:03.650 align:middle line:84%
after the a1 that lies in that
interval you're focusing on.

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:06.630 align:middle line:84%
That's the second element
in the subsequence.

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:11.230 align:middle line:84%
And the b's will always be the
left endpoint of the interval.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:15.030 align:middle line:84%
The c's will be the right
endpoint of the interval.

00:18:15.030 --> 00:18:17.830 align:middle line:84%
Then when you do
the third element,

00:18:17.830 --> 00:18:20.630 align:middle line:84%
then you have to
remember that you were

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:22.950 align:middle line:90%
looking at infinitely many.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:25.350 align:middle line:84%
And so now it's like
you're looking at-- you

00:18:25.350 --> 00:18:28.630 align:middle line:90%
divide this interval into two.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:32.070 align:middle line:84%
And now either this
one here or that one

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:35.190 align:middle line:90%
here has infinitely many.

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:37.090 align:middle line:90%
And you pick whatever it is.

00:18:37.090 --> 00:18:40.590 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I guess we assume
it was this interval.

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:44.950 align:middle line:84%
And then the next element
after the two first you

00:18:44.950 --> 00:18:48.190 align:middle line:84%
picked in the original
sequence, the next element that

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:51.110 align:middle line:84%
lies in this, that's going
to be your third element

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:52.630 align:middle line:90%
of the sequence.

00:18:52.630 --> 00:18:56.470 align:middle line:84%
And then still, the
b's will be then

00:18:56.470 --> 00:18:58.030 align:middle line:84%
of this interval
you're focusing on

00:18:58.030 --> 00:19:01.790 align:middle line:84%
would be the left endpoint
and the c, the right endpoint.

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:06.430 align:middle line:84%
If you do that, you see
each time you're halving it.

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:08.650 align:middle line:84%
So it means--
well, first of all,

00:19:08.650 --> 00:19:13.870 align:middle line:84%
it means that the b's are
going to be increasing,

00:19:13.870 --> 00:19:20.430 align:middle line:84%
because it's always by each
time you divide into a half,

00:19:20.430 --> 00:19:21.590 align:middle line:90%
and it's always--

00:19:21.590 --> 00:19:24.590 align:middle line:84%
but the interval you
focus on previously

00:19:24.590 --> 00:19:26.710 align:middle line:90%
you divide into half, like this.

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:30.850 align:middle line:84%
And then either you pick either
this point or that point.

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:33.510 align:middle line:90%
And this was the previous one.

00:19:33.510 --> 00:19:36.470 align:middle line:84%
So the b's will
always be increasing.

00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:41.430 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, the c's will
be a decreasing sequence.

00:19:41.430 --> 00:19:47.190 align:middle line:84%
And you also see that the
difference between ck--

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:52.870 align:middle line:90%
say, ck plus 1 minus bk plus 1--

00:19:52.870 --> 00:19:56.390 align:middle line:84%
that the difference
here, but the difference

00:19:56.390 --> 00:20:00.910 align:middle line:84%
is going to be like half of the
length of the previous interval.

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:04.870 align:middle line:84%
So the difference here
is going to be 1/2--

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:14.910 align:middle line:84%
it's actually going to be
1/2 and then bck minus bk.

00:20:14.910 --> 00:20:17.950 align:middle line:84%
So you're getting
this form here.

00:20:17.950 --> 00:20:22.670 align:middle line:84%
And now if you just use
that you're starting with--

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:25.790 align:middle line:84%
if you're just using that
there are [INAUDIBLE],

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:30.090 align:middle line:84%
so you get this
recursive formula here.

00:20:30.090 --> 00:20:36.790 align:middle line:84%
And you also have
that c1 minus b1.

00:20:36.790 --> 00:20:40.430 align:middle line:84%
This is the length of
the original interval,

00:20:40.430 --> 00:20:44.630 align:middle line:90%
because b1 was 0, c1 was 1.

00:20:44.630 --> 00:20:47.030 align:middle line:90%
So this is 1.

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:49.150 align:middle line:84%
And so you're just
putting this in.

00:20:49.150 --> 00:20:57.870 align:middle line:84%
And so you get the formula
that ck minus bk is equal to 2

00:20:57.870 --> 00:21:01.830 align:middle line:90%
to the 1 minus k.

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:05.470 align:middle line:84%
So you're getting
this formula here.

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:09.430 align:middle line:84%
This just comes from
this recursive formula

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:11.710 align:middle line:90%
and how this starts.

00:21:11.710 --> 00:21:13.070 align:middle line:90%
So this gives you this.

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:16.430 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that the
length of this interval

00:21:16.430 --> 00:21:18.390 align:middle line:90%
becomes smaller and smaller.

00:21:18.390 --> 00:21:22.190 align:middle line:84%
Again, the sequence
bk is increasing.

00:21:22.190 --> 00:21:25.230 align:middle line:90%
The ck is decreasing.

00:21:25.230 --> 00:21:29.090 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this here
is converging to some b.

00:21:29.090 --> 00:21:31.480 align:middle line:90%
This is converging to some c.

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:35.080 align:middle line:84%
And because the difference
between these goes to 0,

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:37.644 align:middle line:90%
then the b must be equal to c.

00:21:37.644 --> 00:21:40.920 align:middle line:90%


00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:45.920 align:middle line:84%
And so this will prove that
the limit that you construct,

00:21:45.920 --> 00:21:54.240 align:middle line:84%
because this is
going to be squeezed,

00:21:54.240 --> 00:22:00.520 align:middle line:84%
you will have this property
that if you're looking at ak

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:02.880 align:middle line:90%
and even--

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:12.800 align:middle line:84%
sorry, ank and even
anl, the addition here,

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:19.200 align:middle line:84%
this here will, by construction,
will lie between these two.

00:22:19.200 --> 00:22:23.720 align:middle line:84%
But all the later ones will
also lie in this interval.

00:22:23.720 --> 00:22:28.240 align:middle line:84%
So this here will also
lie in this interval,

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:32.060 align:middle line:84%
ck, as long as l here
is bigger or equal to k.

00:22:32.060 --> 00:22:34.760 align:middle line:90%


00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:38.760 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
thing here, this thing here

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:42.780 align:middle line:84%
will-- because this
here is converging to b,

00:22:42.780 --> 00:22:45.000 align:middle line:84%
and actually now, we
prove that this converges

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.160 align:middle line:84%
to the same number, b, so this
means that these guys here

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:50.840 align:middle line:84%
that is squeezed between
these two other sequence

00:22:50.840 --> 00:22:54.740 align:middle line:90%
will also converge to b.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:57.300 align:middle line:84%
So that's a
Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem.

00:22:57.300 --> 00:23:00.400 align:middle line:90%


00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:05.840 align:middle line:84%
OK, another key
concept in this class

00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:07.970 align:middle line:90%
is the concept of a series.

00:23:07.970 --> 00:23:17.720 align:middle line:90%


00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:28.706 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
concept of a series, oops.

00:23:28.706 --> 00:23:32.280 align:middle line:90%


00:23:32.280 --> 00:23:35.600 align:middle line:84%
And so a series is
like as follows,

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:40.770 align:middle line:84%
that suppose you have--
so let an be a sequence.

00:23:40.770 --> 00:23:45.480 align:middle line:90%


00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:49.120 align:middle line:84%
From a sequence, you can
form another sequence.

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And you can form
another sequence

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:57.490 align:middle line:84%
in the following way, that s--
so we form another sequence.

00:23:57.490 --> 00:24:03.320 align:middle line:90%


00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:07.280 align:middle line:90%
And that is that s1.

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:13.520 align:middle line:84%
And we call this other sequence
sn, another sequence, sn.

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:20.640 align:middle line:84%
And the sequence is defined
as follows, that s1 is a1,

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:32.450 align:middle line:84%
s2 is a1 plus a2, s3
is a1 plus a2 plus a3.

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:36.040 align:middle line:90%


00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:40.280 align:middle line:84%
s4 is where you're summing
the first four elements

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:42.930 align:middle line:90%
in the original sequence.

00:24:42.930 --> 00:24:45.720 align:middle line:90%


00:24:45.720 --> 00:24:47.680 align:middle line:90%
And then you write--

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:49.860 align:middle line:84%
sorry, this is the
first four element.

00:24:49.860 --> 00:24:52.480 align:middle line:84%
And then you write
the n-th element.

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:59.590 align:middle line:84%
You write it just as a sum where
i equals to 1 to n of the ai's.

00:24:59.590 --> 00:25:03.200 align:middle line:90%


00:25:03.200 --> 00:25:08.680 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a sequence, then
you can form another sequence.

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:11.840 align:middle line:90%
And this we denote by s.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:15.760 align:middle line:90%
And this here is--

00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:21.180 align:middle line:84%
so this here, other sequence,
if a sequence is of this form,

00:25:21.180 --> 00:25:28.640 align:middle line:84%
then you call it a
series, so sn here.

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:29.260 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:25:29.260 --> 00:25:31.240 align:middle line:90%
But sn is just a sequence.

00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:39.530 align:middle line:84%
This here is said
to be a series.

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:42.440 align:middle line:90%


00:25:42.440 --> 00:25:53.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's go to the most-- so
I'm sure probably everybody have

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:57.560 align:middle line:84%
heard about this kind of one
of the famous Greek paradoxes

00:25:57.560 --> 00:25:58.360 align:middle line:90%
is this.

00:25:58.360 --> 00:26:00.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they have
various different forms.

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:07.120 align:middle line:84%
This is one form of it is
with Achilles and the turtle,

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:10.640 align:middle line:84%
where the turtle is getting
a head start of Achilles.

00:26:10.640 --> 00:26:15.340 align:middle line:84%
And the paradox is that because
the turtle have a head start,

00:26:15.340 --> 00:26:18.180 align:middle line:84%
then Achilles can never
catch up with the turtle,

00:26:18.180 --> 00:26:21.680 align:middle line:84%
even though the turtle is
moving incredibly slowly,

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:24.780 align:middle line:84%
because in order to
catch up with the turtle,

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:30.760 align:middle line:84%
then Achilles first have
to go half of the distance

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:33.280 align:middle line:90%
that the turtle have gone.

00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:34.920 align:middle line:84%
And then once you've
done that, you

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:38.800 align:middle line:84%
have to go half of the
distance that the turtle now

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:41.080 align:middle line:90%
has traveled, et cetera.

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:43.940 align:middle line:84%
And so this goes
on infinitely long,

00:26:43.940 --> 00:26:46.300 align:middle line:84%
and therefore, he can never
catch up with the turtle.

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:49.820 align:middle line:84%
There's various other
version of this.

00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:52.080 align:middle line:90%
And that's exactly a series.

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:56.680 align:middle line:84%
And this is also like
the most important series

00:26:56.680 --> 00:27:01.230 align:middle line:84%
is what's called the geometric
series, so the geometric series.

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:03.960 align:middle line:90%


00:27:03.960 --> 00:27:08.860 align:middle line:84%
So this is the most
important series.

00:27:08.860 --> 00:27:10.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's the most
important because it's

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:13.160 align:middle line:84%
kind of a non-trivial
series that

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:17.680 align:middle line:84%
can be used to determine
whether other series

00:27:17.680 --> 00:27:25.410 align:middle line:84%
or whether for other sums,
whether this sequence sn,

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:27.690 align:middle line:90%
whether it converges or not.

00:27:27.690 --> 00:27:31.690 align:middle line:84%
So the geometric series
is the following, that c--

00:27:31.690 --> 00:27:33.730 align:middle line:90%
you take some number, c--

00:27:33.730 --> 00:27:39.730 align:middle line:84%
and then you are summing
this number, but to a power.

00:27:39.730 --> 00:27:41.370 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking
at where you have

00:27:41.370 --> 00:27:45.730 align:middle line:90%
some power, say, from 0 to n.

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:47.930 align:middle line:90%
So this means that--

00:27:47.930 --> 00:27:49.530 align:middle line:90%
so this is sn.

00:27:49.530 --> 00:28:00.800 align:middle line:84%
So this means that s serum,
this is just where you have a--

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:05.050 align:middle line:84%
so c to the power 0
by definition is 1.

00:28:05.050 --> 00:28:10.450 align:middle line:84%
And s1 is then when you're
summing c to the power 0

00:28:10.450 --> 00:28:13.410 align:middle line:90%
plus c to the power 1.

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:17.250 align:middle line:90%
So that's just 1 plus c.

00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:32.770 align:middle line:84%
And s2 is then c0 plus
c1 plus c squared.

00:28:32.770 --> 00:28:39.090 align:middle line:84%
So that's just 1 plus c
plus c squared et cetera.

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:43.850 align:middle line:84%
So that's a geometric series
where it's just a number.

00:28:43.850 --> 00:28:51.010 align:middle line:84%
And each time you multiply that
number by itself the n time,

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:53.890 align:middle line:84%
and then you're adding
it to the previous.

00:28:53.890 --> 00:28:55.930 align:middle line:90%
So that's a geometric series.

00:28:55.930 --> 00:29:01.570 align:middle line:84%
And the reason why
this is important

00:29:01.570 --> 00:29:05.290 align:middle line:84%
is that this is very
useful to determine

00:29:05.290 --> 00:29:08.290 align:middle line:84%
whether other series
are convergent or not

00:29:08.290 --> 00:29:11.970 align:middle line:84%
because you could compare it,
you can compare other series

00:29:11.970 --> 00:29:15.730 align:middle line:90%
with the geometric series.

00:29:15.730 --> 00:29:17.970 align:middle line:84%
And the geometric
series is easier

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:21.150 align:middle line:84%
to determine whether it
is convergent or not.

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:24.810 align:middle line:84%
And so this is because of the
following little calculation

00:29:24.810 --> 00:29:25.930 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:29:25.930 --> 00:29:31.690 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose I'm looking at
some summing here from 0 to n

00:29:31.690 --> 00:29:36.210 align:middle line:90%
of c to the power i.

00:29:36.210 --> 00:29:41.970 align:middle line:90%
And now I multiply this with c.

00:29:41.970 --> 00:29:44.690 align:middle line:84%
So then this here
would just be where

00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:47.970 align:middle line:84%
I'm summing here c--
if I multiply by c,

00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:50.490 align:middle line:90%
I can move that c inside.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:54.850 align:middle line:84%
And then the first time
it's really right-- so you

00:29:54.850 --> 00:29:56.190 align:middle line:90%
can write this thing here.

00:29:56.190 --> 00:29:57.390 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write it out.

00:29:57.390 --> 00:29:58.850 align:middle line:90%
So this is c.

00:29:58.850 --> 00:30:05.090 align:middle line:84%
And then it's 1 plus c plus c
squared plus c cubed, et cetera,

00:30:05.090 --> 00:30:06.650 align:middle line:90%
like that, up to cn.

00:30:06.650 --> 00:30:09.410 align:middle line:90%


00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:12.230 align:middle line:84%
And if you multiply
by c, then, of course,

00:30:12.230 --> 00:30:17.170 align:middle line:84%
this is just c plus c
squared plus c cubed up

00:30:17.170 --> 00:30:20.970 align:middle line:90%
to c to the n plus 1.

00:30:20.970 --> 00:30:26.150 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that if
you take this thing here,

00:30:26.150 --> 00:30:31.690 align:middle line:84%
so if you're looking at
the sum from 0 to n of ci,

00:30:31.690 --> 00:30:36.730 align:middle line:84%
and now you multiply
by 1 minus c,

00:30:36.730 --> 00:30:44.190 align:middle line:84%
then this is the same
as just 1 times this.

00:30:44.190 --> 00:30:45.670 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write it out.

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:49.690 align:middle line:84%
This just gives you
the original series.

00:30:49.690 --> 00:30:53.050 align:middle line:90%
So this gives you this up to cn.

00:30:53.050 --> 00:30:55.970 align:middle line:84%
That's when we
multiply the one n.

00:30:55.970 --> 00:30:59.810 align:middle line:84%
When we multiply it by minus
c, then we get this thing

00:30:59.810 --> 00:31:01.630 align:middle line:90%
here with a minus sign.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:05.090 align:middle line:90%
So we're getting minus c.

00:31:05.090 --> 00:31:06.830 align:middle line:90%
So I can write it like this.

00:31:06.830 --> 00:31:11.650 align:middle line:90%


00:31:11.650 --> 00:31:13.690 align:middle line:90%
Like that, right?

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:17.290 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that there's
a lot of cancelation.

00:31:17.290 --> 00:31:21.170 align:middle line:84%
This thing here
cancel with this here.

00:31:21.170 --> 00:31:23.410 align:middle line:84%
The next one would
cancel with this.

00:31:23.410 --> 00:31:26.810 align:middle line:84%
This here would cancel
with the second last.

00:31:26.810 --> 00:31:32.310 align:middle line:84%
And so you are only left with
this one here and that one here.

00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:35.530 align:middle line:84%
But this one here comes
in with a minus sign.

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:40.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1 minus
c to the n plus 1.

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:42.660 align:middle line:90%
So we have this little formula.

00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:49.130 align:middle line:90%


00:31:49.130 --> 00:31:58.610 align:middle line:84%
And this is a formula, say, that
if you take 1 minus c and you

00:31:58.610 --> 00:32:03.570 align:middle line:84%
sum from i equal
to 0 to n of ci--

00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:06.290 align:middle line:90%


00:32:06.290 --> 00:32:08.130 align:middle line:84%
this is what we did
here-- then you're

00:32:08.130 --> 00:32:14.450 align:middle line:84%
getting 1 minus c
to the n plus 1.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:16.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:16.050 --> 00:32:19.530 align:middle line:84%
So now, of course,
if c is 1-- let's

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:21.710 align:middle line:90%
wait with figuring that out.

00:32:21.710 --> 00:32:27.010 align:middle line:84%
But assume that c here
is not equal to 1.

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:33.450 align:middle line:84%
Then I can write this here as
that this sum here, i equal to 0

00:32:33.450 --> 00:32:39.770 align:middle line:84%
to n ci, I can just divide here
by this here on both sides.

00:32:39.770 --> 00:32:43.890 align:middle line:84%
So I get this thing
here, 1 minus c.

00:32:43.890 --> 00:32:49.290 align:middle line:84%
So I have this
formula here, assuming

00:32:49.290 --> 00:32:54.250 align:middle line:84%
that c is not equal to 1, so
I can divide by 1 minus c.

00:32:54.250 --> 00:32:57.770 align:middle line:90%
And now you see that--

00:32:57.770 --> 00:33:02.275 align:middle line:84%
so now from this here,
we can determine-- so we

00:33:02.275 --> 00:33:03.400 align:middle line:90%
can prove a little theorem.

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:07.530 align:middle line:90%


00:33:07.530 --> 00:33:10.330 align:middle line:90%
So that the geometric series--

00:33:10.330 --> 00:33:12.670 align:middle line:84%
so this is geometric
series convergence.

00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:22.320 align:middle line:90%


00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:27.060 align:middle line:84%
Remember that this thing
here, so a series here--

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:29.560 align:middle line:84%
so maybe I should just
emphasize that over here.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:32.460 align:middle line:90%


00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:36.860 align:middle line:84%
So if you write down a
series, so again, a series

00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:41.260 align:middle line:84%
is always that you're starting
with a sequence like this.

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:45.340 align:middle line:84%
And then you form this
other sequence, sn, where

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:50.406 align:middle line:90%
you're summing the first n--

00:33:50.406 --> 00:33:53.720 align:middle line:84%
I guess in this case,
I'm starting from 0.

00:33:53.720 --> 00:34:00.340 align:middle line:84%
So then it would be n plus
1 elements, like this.

00:34:00.340 --> 00:34:05.220 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes one also
just write for the series,

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:14.260 align:middle line:84%
one write it as this,
where one write like this.

00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:19.500 align:middle line:84%
But really, what you're thinking
about is this sequence here.

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:23.960 align:middle line:84%
But you, with a slight
abuse of notation,

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:27.199 align:middle line:90%
you write this here for series.

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:30.460 align:middle line:84%
But what you're thinking
about is this sequence.

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:32.806 align:middle line:90%
And so a series is convergent.

00:34:32.806 --> 00:34:42.460 align:middle line:90%


00:34:42.460 --> 00:34:53.639 align:middle line:84%
It just means that the
sequence sn is convergent.

00:34:53.639 --> 00:34:58.740 align:middle line:90%


00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:05.300 align:middle line:84%
So it just means that this
sequence, sn, is convergent.

00:35:05.300 --> 00:35:13.430 align:middle line:84%
And the sum and the
limit of the series--

00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:16.020 align:middle line:90%


00:35:16.020 --> 00:35:25.420 align:middle line:84%
this is just the limit,
is the limit of the sn's.

00:35:25.420 --> 00:35:30.740 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:47.280 align:middle line:84%
That is usually denoted by
this, by this infinite sum, a.

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:52.260 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, this was
i, ai, like that.

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:52.760 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:56.820 align:middle line:84%
So you see there's a little
bit of abuse of notation,

00:35:56.820 --> 00:36:00.300 align:middle line:84%
that one talk about
a series and one

00:36:00.300 --> 00:36:02.500 align:middle line:90%
typically write it like this.

00:36:02.500 --> 00:36:06.620 align:middle line:84%
What one really means is that
one thing about this sequence

00:36:06.620 --> 00:36:07.860 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:36:07.860 --> 00:36:10.260 align:middle line:84%
And then if it's
convergent, this just

00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:13.940 align:middle line:90%
means that these sn converge.

00:36:13.940 --> 00:36:19.020 align:middle line:84%
And the limit, but the limit
you would also write as this.

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:23.200 align:middle line:84%
So in a way, this symbol here is
used for two different things.

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:25.140 align:middle line:90%
It's used for the series.

00:36:25.140 --> 00:36:30.620 align:middle line:84%
And if the series is convergent,
it's also used for the limit.

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:31.850 align:middle line:90%
This is like standard.

00:36:31.850 --> 00:36:34.420 align:middle line:90%


00:36:34.420 --> 00:36:38.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now let's come back
to the geometric series.

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:43.300 align:middle line:84%
So again, the geometric series
were that you take some c,

00:36:43.300 --> 00:36:47.340 align:middle line:84%
and then you form
this series here,

00:36:47.340 --> 00:36:51.520 align:middle line:90%
ci, i equal to 0 to infinity.

00:36:51.520 --> 00:36:54.480 align:middle line:84%
It's, of course,
important where you start.

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:57.460 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the convergence
is not important.

00:36:57.460 --> 00:37:01.420 align:middle line:84%
But what the limit is
depends on where you start.

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:05.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is a geometric series.

00:37:05.460 --> 00:37:10.540 align:middle line:90%
And we have that if c here--

00:37:10.540 --> 00:37:23.220 align:middle line:84%
so we have now the following,
that the geometric series

00:37:23.220 --> 00:37:35.900 align:middle line:84%
is convergent if c here in
absolute value is less than 1

00:37:35.900 --> 00:37:49.700 align:middle line:84%
and divergent otherwise,
if the absolute value of c

00:37:49.700 --> 00:37:52.140 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than 1.

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:54.970 align:middle line:90%
So this is the claim that--

00:37:54.970 --> 00:37:57.580 align:middle line:90%


00:37:57.580 --> 00:38:00.180 align:middle line:90%
and so this is a claim.

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:10.696 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, so one
more thing is that--

00:38:10.696 --> 00:38:14.700 align:middle line:90%


00:38:14.700 --> 00:38:29.460 align:middle line:84%
so moreover, if c is less
than 1, then the limit--

00:38:29.460 --> 00:38:36.660 align:middle line:84%
so then the claim is that it's
convergent-- then the limit

00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:41.700 align:middle line:90%
is 1 minus c.

00:38:41.700 --> 00:38:42.880 align:middle line:90%
This is the limit.

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:48.210 align:middle line:84%
And so we write this here
as this infinite sum.

00:38:48.210 --> 00:38:53.260 align:middle line:90%


00:38:53.260 --> 00:38:56.940 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's just
try to prove this.

00:38:56.940 --> 00:39:02.660 align:middle line:84%
So let me first do-- and
we're almost there already.

00:39:02.660 --> 00:39:05.760 align:middle line:90%
So the thing is that--

00:39:05.760 --> 00:39:14.430 align:middle line:90%


00:39:14.430 --> 00:39:16.300 align:middle line:90%
so let's first look at the case.

00:39:16.300 --> 00:39:21.310 align:middle line:90%


00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:29.070 align:middle line:84%
Assume c in absolute value
is strictly less than 1.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:36.030 align:middle line:84%
But then we have already
proven that sn is-- so sn,

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:41.310 align:middle line:84%
this here was the sum from
i equal to 0 to n of ci.

00:39:41.310 --> 00:39:46.470 align:middle line:84%
And we have already proven that
this is 1 minus cn plus 1 over 1

00:39:46.470 --> 00:39:48.990 align:middle line:90%
minus c.

00:39:48.990 --> 00:39:51.350 align:middle line:90%
And this makes sense.

00:39:51.350 --> 00:39:53.130 align:middle line:90%
Norm is strictly less than 1.

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:55.290 align:middle line:84%
So in particular,
c is not 1, right?

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:57.710 align:middle line:90%
So this here is fine.

00:39:57.710 --> 00:39:59.670 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
if you take something

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:04.430 align:middle line:84%
with norm strictly less
than 1, then just because cn

00:40:04.430 --> 00:40:10.190 align:middle line:84%
plus 1, the norm of this here,
but if you take something

00:40:10.190 --> 00:40:14.630 align:middle line:84%
and you multiply it by another--
so if you take two numbers, a

00:40:14.630 --> 00:40:17.630 align:middle line:84%
and b, and you take
the absolute value

00:40:17.630 --> 00:40:20.430 align:middle line:84%
of the product, that's
the same as the product

00:40:20.430 --> 00:40:23.310 align:middle line:90%
of the absolute values.

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:27.990 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if you
take c to the power n plus 1--

00:40:27.990 --> 00:40:29.950 align:middle line:84%
so if you take c
and you multiply it

00:40:29.950 --> 00:40:33.670 align:middle line:84%
by itself n plus 1
time, this is the same

00:40:33.670 --> 00:40:37.030 align:middle line:84%
as the absolute value
times [INAUDIBLE] raised

00:40:37.030 --> 00:40:39.650 align:middle line:90%
to the power n plus 1 right.

00:40:39.650 --> 00:40:42.710 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see
that because this c has

00:40:42.710 --> 00:40:46.950 align:middle line:84%
absolute value less than
1, strictly less than 1,

00:40:46.950 --> 00:40:52.350 align:middle line:84%
then as n goes to infinity,
this here converges to 0.

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:55.910 align:middle line:84%
So this means that as
n goes to infinity,

00:40:55.910 --> 00:40:59.150 align:middle line:90%
this thing here might converge.

00:40:59.150 --> 00:41:00.870 align:middle line:90%
This here goes to 0.

00:41:00.870 --> 00:41:05.270 align:middle line:84%
So just by the algebraic
rules for limits,

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:10.670 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is going to
converge to 1 minus c over 1,

00:41:10.670 --> 00:41:11.430 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:41:11.430 --> 00:41:14.710 align:middle line:90%


00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:20.830 align:middle line:84%
So you see that in the case
where c in absolute value

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:23.790 align:middle line:84%
is strictly less than
1, then we have now

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:26.810 align:middle line:84%
proven that the geometric
series is convergent.

00:41:26.810 --> 00:41:30.230 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, we have even,
which is really nice,

00:41:30.230 --> 00:41:34.090 align:middle line:90%
and unusual for a series.

00:41:34.090 --> 00:41:37.190 align:middle line:84%
I mean, usually you cannot
actually determine what

00:41:37.190 --> 00:41:38.270 align:middle line:90%
the limit is.

00:41:38.270 --> 00:41:39.790 align:middle line:90%
But in this case, we could.

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:43.070 align:middle line:84%
But we still need
to figure out why

00:41:43.070 --> 00:41:51.790 align:middle line:84%
is it not convergent if
the absolute value of c

00:41:51.790 --> 00:41:54.710 align:middle line:90%
is bigger or equal to 1.

00:41:54.710 --> 00:41:58.350 align:middle line:90%
And so here's an easy thing.

00:41:58.350 --> 00:42:00.950 align:middle line:90%
I mean, but you could also--

00:42:00.950 --> 00:42:04.710 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so here's an easy thing,
that if you're looking at c--

00:42:04.710 --> 00:42:14.590 align:middle line:84%
sorry, sn plus 1 minus sn,
where sn plus 1 or sn say,

00:42:14.590 --> 00:42:23.850 align:middle line:84%
this here was just c to the
power 0 up to c to the power n.

00:42:23.850 --> 00:42:28.950 align:middle line:84%
Sn plus 1 is where
you do the same stuff.

00:42:28.950 --> 00:42:32.190 align:middle line:90%
We're adding these guys.

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:36.630 align:middle line:84%
But then you have to
add one more, right?

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:40.230 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this
difference here is really

00:42:40.230 --> 00:42:45.190 align:middle line:90%
c to the n plus 1, right?

00:42:45.190 --> 00:42:47.990 align:middle line:84%
But now I could look
at the absolute value

00:42:47.990 --> 00:42:50.670 align:middle line:90%
of this difference.

00:42:50.670 --> 00:42:53.790 align:middle line:90%
This is this.

00:42:53.790 --> 00:43:00.470 align:middle line:84%
But this is the same, again,
as c to the power n plus 1.

00:43:00.470 --> 00:43:05.470 align:middle line:84%
But you see, if c here is
the absolute value is bigger

00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:09.070 align:middle line:84%
or equal to 1, then
this thing here-- oops--

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:12.630 align:middle line:84%
then this thing here, so
if the absolute value here

00:43:12.630 --> 00:43:16.070 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal to
1, then this thing here

00:43:16.070 --> 00:43:19.630 align:middle line:90%
must be bigger or equal to 1.

00:43:19.630 --> 00:43:23.290 align:middle line:84%
Remember that if a
sequence is convergent,

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:27.830 align:middle line:84%
if a sequence is convergent,
then it is a Cauchy sequence.

00:43:27.830 --> 00:43:31.430 align:middle line:84%
It's a Cauchy sequence that
if you go sufficiently far

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:36.710 align:middle line:84%
out, then from there on and
out, everything bunch very, very

00:43:36.710 --> 00:43:37.890 align:middle line:90%
close together.

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:41.230 align:middle line:84%
But you see here, not
even two consecutive

00:43:41.230 --> 00:43:44.990 align:middle line:84%
is bunching together, because
independent on how far,

00:43:44.990 --> 00:43:49.110 align:middle line:84%
how large n is, the difference
is always at least 1.

00:43:49.110 --> 00:43:51.110 align:middle line:90%
So this is not even a Cauchy--

00:43:51.110 --> 00:43:53.850 align:middle line:84%
I mean, well, it's actually
equivalent, of course,

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:55.370 align:middle line:90%
but it's not a Cauchy sequence.

00:43:55.370 --> 00:43:56.910 align:middle line:90%
It's failed.

00:43:56.910 --> 00:44:00.470 align:middle line:84%
Like the most basic thing
with consecutive ones

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:03.870 align:middle line:84%
does not even lie
close together.

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:09.550 align:middle line:84%
So this proves this theorem
about the geometric convergence,

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:12.630 align:middle line:84%
the geometric
series convergence.

00:44:12.630 --> 00:44:23.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is the most important
example of a sequence.

00:44:23.750 --> 00:44:28.270 align:middle line:84%
Maybe the second
most important is

00:44:28.270 --> 00:44:35.920 align:middle line:84%
what's called the harmonic
series, so harmonic series.

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:44.750 align:middle line:90%


00:44:44.750 --> 00:44:48.830 align:middle line:84%
But the harmonic series is
unfortunately not a series

00:44:48.830 --> 00:44:50.670 align:middle line:90%
that is convergent.

00:44:50.670 --> 00:44:52.770 align:middle line:84%
So the harmonic series
is the following.

00:44:52.770 --> 00:44:54.150 align:middle line:90%
So again, I'm writing it--

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:59.440 align:middle line:84%
I'm using this abusive notation
that I'm writing the series as

00:44:59.440 --> 00:45:01.280 align:middle line:90%
like an infinite sum.

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:06.540 align:middle line:84%
But this infinite sum, but
it's not a convergent series,

00:45:06.540 --> 00:45:08.920 align:middle line:84%
so the infinite sum
doesn't really make sense.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:14.460 align:middle line:84%
So here I have to start
because I'm dividing by n.

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:16.560 align:middle line:90%
So I'm starting by 1 with 1.

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:19.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is called
the harmonic series.

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:20.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:20.300 --> 00:45:31.280 align:middle line:84%
And so for series,
there's a bunch

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:34.120 align:middle line:84%
of things, a bunch
of tests that are

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:37.420 align:middle line:84%
useful to determine whether a
series is convergent or not.

00:45:37.420 --> 00:45:41.720 align:middle line:90%


00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:43.640 align:middle line:84%
And we will talk
about these tests.

00:45:43.640 --> 00:45:45.980 align:middle line:84%
I'll talk a little bit
about later in this lecture.

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:48.820 align:middle line:84%
I'll talk about some of the
tests, but not all of them.

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:51.760 align:middle line:84%
And we will later
talk about more.

00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:55.020 align:middle line:84%
The test that is particularly
useful in this case,

00:45:55.020 --> 00:45:56.580 align:middle line:84%
it's what's called
the integral test.

00:45:56.580 --> 00:45:59.760 align:middle line:84%
But I won't talk
about that today.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:05.560 align:middle line:84%
But instead, I will show you
a very simple proof of why

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:09.020 align:middle line:90%
this here is not convergent.

00:46:09.020 --> 00:46:12.000 align:middle line:90%


00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:15.750 align:middle line:90%
So here's a theorem.

00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:19.920 align:middle line:90%


00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:30.162 align:middle line:84%
The harmonic series
is a divergence.

00:46:30.162 --> 00:46:31.120 align:middle line:90%
So it's not convergent.

00:46:31.120 --> 00:46:32.100 align:middle line:90%
It's divergent.

00:46:32.100 --> 00:46:34.680 align:middle line:90%


00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:37.000 align:middle line:84%
And so in fact,
what we will prove

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:44.080 align:middle line:84%
is the following, that we will
show that if you're looking at--

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:46.240 align:middle line:90%
so n is an integer.

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:48.820 align:middle line:90%
If you're looking at--

00:46:48.820 --> 00:46:51.200 align:middle line:90%
so this is like--

00:46:51.200 --> 00:46:57.920 align:middle line:84%
so this is only some of the--
you only hit, for this here,

00:46:57.920 --> 00:47:03.200 align:middle line:84%
you only hit some of the
elements in the sequence.

00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:11.120 align:middle line:84%
So this is where I'm summing
again from i equal to 1 to 2

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:16.760 align:middle line:84%
to the n minus 1, n is
an integer, of 1 over i.

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:21.280 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove
that these guys here,

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:24.900 align:middle line:84%
if the original sequence
had been convergent,

00:47:24.900 --> 00:47:28.400 align:middle line:84%
then of course, any subsequence
would also be convergent.

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:32.440 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to prove
that this thing here

00:47:32.440 --> 00:47:36.000 align:middle line:90%
is bigger or equal to n over 2.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:37.820 align:middle line:90%
So I claim that we have this.

00:47:37.820 --> 00:47:44.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is a claim
that you have this.

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:47.440 align:middle line:84%
But if you have this
thing here, you see,

00:47:47.440 --> 00:47:51.340 align:middle line:84%
that then this subsequence
here is unbounded.

00:47:51.340 --> 00:47:54.640 align:middle line:84%
So of course, the
original harmonic series

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:57.280 align:middle line:90%
is not convergent.

00:47:57.280 --> 00:47:59.440 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove this.

00:47:59.440 --> 00:48:06.320 align:middle line:84%
Again, this is just like
a simple proof of that--

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:09.280 align:middle line:84%
very simple-minded proof--
that the harmonic series

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:11.040 align:middle line:90%
is divergent.

00:48:11.040 --> 00:48:12.953 align:middle line:90%
But there are more.

00:48:12.953 --> 00:48:15.960 align:middle line:90%


00:48:15.960 --> 00:48:18.700 align:middle line:84%
Once we learn about the
integral test and so on,

00:48:18.700 --> 00:48:24.520 align:middle line:84%
there are other way
better ways of doing it.

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:26.220 align:middle line:90%
So let me try to prove this.

00:48:26.220 --> 00:48:31.310 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove the
claim, proof of the claim.

00:48:31.310 --> 00:48:37.080 align:middle line:90%


00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:38.860 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to prove it, right?

00:48:38.860 --> 00:48:40.440 align:middle line:90%
So I just proved.

00:48:40.440 --> 00:48:43.440 align:middle line:84%
So I want to establish
this for all n.

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:51.960 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to prove it
first when n is equal to 1.

00:48:51.960 --> 00:48:55.920 align:middle line:84%
So let's show this
for n equal to 1.

00:48:55.920 --> 00:49:05.100 align:middle line:84%
So for n equal to 1, well then,
the claim here means that--

00:49:05.100 --> 00:49:07.600 align:middle line:90%
so 2 to the 1, that's true.

00:49:07.600 --> 00:49:16.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is s1, right, because
2 to the 1 is 2 minus 1.

00:49:16.020 --> 00:49:17.400 align:middle line:90%
So this is 1.

00:49:17.400 --> 00:49:19.720 align:middle line:90%
So I claim that.

00:49:19.720 --> 00:49:25.920 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove that s1
is bigger or equal to 1/2.

00:49:25.920 --> 00:49:26.860 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE] to show.

00:49:26.860 --> 00:49:30.000 align:middle line:90%


00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:36.280 align:middle line:84%
But of course, s1 here,
s1 is just 1 over 1.

00:49:36.280 --> 00:49:40.040 align:middle line:90%
So that's definitely fine.

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:47.240 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so we want
to prove the claim.

00:49:47.240 --> 00:49:49.640 align:middle line:90%
And the claim is OK.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:56.120 align:middle line:90%
So claim is OK for n equal to 1.

00:49:56.120 --> 00:49:58.740 align:middle line:90%
So now I want to prove it.

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:15.160 align:middle line:84%
So I want to assume the
claim is correct for n.

00:50:15.160 --> 00:50:22.440 align:middle line:84%
And we want to prove
it for, want to show

00:50:22.440 --> 00:50:30.060 align:middle line:90%
the claim for the next one.

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:33.300 align:middle line:90%
And so I have that.

00:50:33.300 --> 00:50:43.880 align:middle line:84%
So we assume that s2n
minus 1, that this

00:50:43.880 --> 00:50:47.840 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than n over 2.

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:55.270 align:middle line:84%
And then I want to look
at s2n plus 1 minus 1.

00:50:55.270 --> 00:50:58.450 align:middle line:84%
OK, how can I write
this thing here?

00:50:58.450 --> 00:51:00.990 align:middle line:90%
So I'm summing, right?

00:51:00.990 --> 00:51:04.290 align:middle line:84%
This here is a sum of
the 1 over i, where

00:51:04.290 --> 00:51:06.690 align:middle line:90%
I do it up to this thing here.

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:10.330 align:middle line:84%
But I can think about
that as the sum of the one

00:51:10.330 --> 00:51:14.530 align:middle line:90%
where I do up to this here.

00:51:14.530 --> 00:51:20.210 align:middle line:84%
And then I have to
sum the rest also.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:34.370 align:middle line:84%
So this is i equal to 2n, to
2n plus 1, 2n plus 1 minus 1,

00:51:34.370 --> 00:51:38.090 align:middle line:90%
like this, of 1 over i.

00:51:38.090 --> 00:51:47.000 align:middle line:84%
But now you see, I want
a bounded from below.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:47.500 align:middle line:90%
Fine.

00:51:47.500 --> 00:51:50.090 align:middle line:90%


00:51:50.090 --> 00:51:54.450 align:middle line:84%
So if you continue this
line, then by assumption,

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:58.730 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is
bounded by n over 2.

00:51:58.730 --> 00:52:05.870 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, I'm
summing 2n numbers.

00:52:05.870 --> 00:52:10.770 align:middle line:84%
From here to here,
there are 2n numbers.

00:52:10.770 --> 00:52:16.570 align:middle line:90%
And so it's 2n numbers.

00:52:16.570 --> 00:52:20.210 align:middle line:84%
And if I take the smallest
of those two numbers,

00:52:20.210 --> 00:52:24.650 align:middle line:84%
if I take the smallest of these
guys and I multiply it by 2n,

00:52:24.650 --> 00:52:26.510 align:middle line:84%
then that's definitely
a lower bound.

00:52:26.510 --> 00:52:27.710 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to do this.

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:30.010 align:middle line:90%
So I say 2n, 2 to the n--

00:52:30.010 --> 00:52:33.690 align:middle line:84%
and then the smallest, but
the smallest is the last one.

00:52:33.690 --> 00:52:40.570 align:middle line:84%
So the smallest is 1 over
2 to the n plus 1 minus 1.

00:52:40.570 --> 00:52:47.490 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is, of
course, obviously bigger

00:52:47.490 --> 00:52:51.590 align:middle line:84%
than-- so n over 2, this thing
here-- well, this is true, then.

00:52:51.590 --> 00:52:55.650 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here,
if I divide by a larger

00:52:55.650 --> 00:52:59.170 align:middle line:84%
number and the larger
number is just this here,

00:52:59.170 --> 00:53:01.610 align:middle line:84%
then I get something
even smaller.

00:53:01.610 --> 00:53:05.970 align:middle line:84%
So I would have 1 over
2 to the n plus 1.

00:53:05.970 --> 00:53:11.250 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that this thing
here cancel with these guys

00:53:11.250 --> 00:53:12.290 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:53:12.290 --> 00:53:17.370 align:middle line:84%
And so you're getting that
this is n over 2 plus 1/2.

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:20.190 align:middle line:90%
And so this is n plus 1 over 2.

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:25.170 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly the
claim for n plus 1.

00:53:25.170 --> 00:53:28.490 align:middle line:84%
So we're proven that if
it was true for n, then

00:53:28.490 --> 00:53:30.810 align:middle line:90%
it's also true for n plus 1.

00:53:30.810 --> 00:53:37.330 align:middle line:84%
And we remember to check that
the beginning was also OK.

00:53:37.330 --> 00:53:38.950 align:middle line:90%
So that's a harmonic series.

00:53:38.950 --> 00:53:43.530 align:middle line:84%
So you see that the harmonic
series is divergent.

00:53:43.530 --> 00:53:48.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, the harmonic
series is, of course,

00:53:48.150 --> 00:53:54.810 align:middle line:84%
an example of something else,
namely that if you're looking

00:53:54.810 --> 00:53:58.970 align:middle line:84%
at-- so when you're
looking at a series,

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:01.430 align:middle line:84%
the first thing you
look at typically is--

00:54:01.430 --> 00:54:07.650 align:middle line:90%


00:54:07.650 --> 00:54:12.310 align:middle line:84%
OK, so let me just
have a side here.

00:54:12.310 --> 00:54:17.490 align:middle line:90%
So if you give me a series--

00:54:17.490 --> 00:54:19.370 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't really matter where.

00:54:19.370 --> 00:54:24.290 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it doesn't matter
very much where it's--

00:54:24.290 --> 00:54:27.190 align:middle line:84%
for whether a series
is convergent,

00:54:27.190 --> 00:54:29.010 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter
where you start,

00:54:29.010 --> 00:54:32.610 align:middle line:84%
because this is just
adding something to it.

00:54:32.610 --> 00:54:34.910 align:middle line:84%
It will matter where
you start for the limit,

00:54:34.910 --> 00:54:38.650 align:middle line:84%
but not whether or not
the series is convergent.

00:54:38.650 --> 00:54:42.450 align:middle line:84%
But if you give me a limit,
the first thing I always check

00:54:42.450 --> 00:54:44.230 align:middle line:90%
is that this--

00:54:44.230 --> 00:54:59.420 align:middle line:84%
so first, so for a series,
always check if an goes to 0

00:54:59.420 --> 00:54:59.920 align:middle line:90%
or not.

00:54:59.920 --> 00:55:02.930 align:middle line:90%


00:55:02.930 --> 00:55:04.130 align:middle line:90%
And why?

00:55:04.130 --> 00:55:09.210 align:middle line:84%
Because if you give me a series,
the question about a series

00:55:09.210 --> 00:55:11.530 align:middle line:84%
is always whether it's
converging or not.

00:55:11.530 --> 00:55:18.450 align:middle line:84%
And again, just like we did,
if you're looking at sn, say,

00:55:18.450 --> 00:55:21.890 align:middle line:84%
minus sn minus 1, this
is where I'm looking

00:55:21.890 --> 00:55:23.770 align:middle line:90%
at two consecutive things.

00:55:23.770 --> 00:55:27.330 align:middle line:84%
But if I'm looking at
this difference here,

00:55:27.330 --> 00:55:31.350 align:middle line:84%
the difference here, this is
where I'm summing up to the a,

00:55:31.350 --> 00:55:32.930 align:middle line:90%
n minus 1.

00:55:32.930 --> 00:55:35.050 align:middle line:90%
Here I'm summing up to the an.

00:55:35.050 --> 00:55:38.290 align:middle line:90%
So the difference here is an.

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.170 align:middle line:84%
And if the sequence--
just like we

00:55:40.170 --> 00:55:43.990 align:middle line:84%
saw, if the sequence of
the series is convergent,

00:55:43.990 --> 00:55:47.150 align:middle line:84%
it means that this sequence
here is convergent.

00:55:47.150 --> 00:55:50.050 align:middle line:84%
But it means that it has to be
a Cauchy sequence, that things

00:55:50.050 --> 00:55:55.570 align:middle line:84%
have to bunch together, but that
two consecutive bunch together

00:55:55.570 --> 00:55:58.630 align:middle line:84%
is determined whether
an goes to 0 or not.

00:55:58.630 --> 00:56:03.350 align:middle line:84%
So if an does not go to 0,
you're already done, right?

00:56:03.350 --> 00:56:05.210 align:middle line:90%
There's no reason to continue.

00:56:05.210 --> 00:56:08.730 align:middle line:84%
It's already clear that
if an does not go to 0,

00:56:08.730 --> 00:56:10.930 align:middle line:84%
you can just say it
doesn't converge,

00:56:10.930 --> 00:56:12.590 align:middle line:90%
because an doesn't go to 0.

00:56:12.590 --> 00:56:14.770 align:middle line:84%
So there's no reason to
start with any kind of test

00:56:14.770 --> 00:56:18.640 align:middle line:84%
or anything, any
sort of good ideas.

00:56:18.640 --> 00:56:22.410 align:middle line:90%


00:56:22.410 --> 00:56:25.610 align:middle line:90%
So that was just a side remark.

00:56:25.610 --> 00:56:29.730 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is that
for the harmonic series

00:56:29.730 --> 00:56:33.420 align:middle line:84%
is-- so this, of course,
failed this test.

00:56:33.420 --> 00:56:35.930 align:middle line:90%


00:56:35.930 --> 00:56:42.340 align:middle line:84%
But it also is an example of
something where you're taking--

00:56:42.340 --> 00:56:43.820 align:middle line:90%
so suppose you take a--

00:56:43.820 --> 00:56:47.640 align:middle line:90%
so you have a sequence, an.

00:56:47.640 --> 00:56:55.860 align:middle line:84%
And then you're forming the
series, this series here.

00:56:55.860 --> 00:56:57.450 align:middle line:90%
Now, if all of a n's--

00:56:57.450 --> 00:57:00.190 align:middle line:90%


00:57:00.190 --> 00:57:04.220 align:middle line:84%
you post that all of the
a n's are non-negative,

00:57:04.220 --> 00:57:11.140 align:middle line:84%
then if you're looking at sn
plus 1, you can think about sn

00:57:11.140 --> 00:57:18.500 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 as where you're
summing the first n elements,

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:22.680 align:middle line:84%
and then you're adding
the n plus 1 element.

00:57:22.680 --> 00:57:30.260 align:middle line:84%
So this here you can think
about as sn plus an plus 1.

00:57:30.260 --> 00:57:34.980 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, if all of
these elements is non-negative,

00:57:34.980 --> 00:57:36.760 align:middle line:84%
this means that this
has non-negative.

00:57:36.760 --> 00:57:39.700 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is bigger than sn.

00:57:39.700 --> 00:57:43.340 align:middle line:84%
So you see that if all of the
element, an, is non-negative,

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:47.640 align:middle line:84%
then this sequence,
sn, is monotone.

00:57:47.640 --> 00:57:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So in this case here,
if you have this,

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:56.180 align:middle line:84%
this imply that this sn
is monotone increasing.

00:57:56.180 --> 00:58:01.140 align:middle line:84%
And so now to say whether
this, if you have this,

00:58:01.140 --> 00:58:05.580 align:middle line:84%
to determine whether this series
here is convergent or not,

00:58:05.580 --> 00:58:10.180 align:middle line:84%
it's just a matter of
proving whether to determine

00:58:10.180 --> 00:58:15.155 align:middle line:84%
whether this sequence
is bounded or not.

00:58:15.155 --> 00:58:16.530 align:middle line:84%
So you just need
to find a bound.

00:58:16.530 --> 00:58:19.620 align:middle line:90%


00:58:19.620 --> 00:58:24.180 align:middle line:84%
So this naturally leads
to looking at what's

00:58:24.180 --> 00:58:27.420 align:middle line:90%
called absolute convergence.

00:58:27.420 --> 00:58:30.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is something
stronger than convergence.

00:58:30.080 --> 00:58:33.180 align:middle line:90%


00:58:33.180 --> 00:58:35.500 align:middle line:90%
And for many things--

00:58:35.500 --> 00:58:38.540 align:middle line:90%
for many, although not all--

00:58:38.540 --> 00:58:40.340 align:middle line:84%
there is a particular
test that deals

00:58:40.340 --> 00:58:46.780 align:middle line:84%
with it where you don't have
both things or you [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:46.780 --> 00:58:48.060 align:middle line:90%
have a stronger property.

00:58:48.060 --> 00:58:54.500 align:middle line:84%
So for many things you
have absolute convergence.

00:58:54.500 --> 00:59:00.680 align:middle line:84%
And so let me try to--
so absolute convergence.

00:59:00.680 --> 00:59:09.100 align:middle line:90%


00:59:09.100 --> 00:59:13.080 align:middle line:84%
So again, you have
a series here.

00:59:13.080 --> 00:59:17.220 align:middle line:90%


00:59:17.220 --> 00:59:21.400 align:middle line:84%
This series here is said to be
absolute convergence or converge

00:59:21.400 --> 00:59:27.300 align:middle line:84%
absolutely-- so
converge absolutely--

00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:31.620 align:middle line:90%


00:59:31.620 --> 00:59:38.340 align:middle line:84%
if the series where you slap
absolute values on them,

00:59:38.340 --> 00:59:41.410 align:middle line:90%
if this thing here, converge.

00:59:41.410 --> 00:59:51.400 align:middle line:90%


00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:54.020 align:middle line:84%
So we say that this
here converge absolutely

00:59:54.020 --> 00:59:55.700 align:middle line:90%
if this here converge.

00:59:55.700 --> 01:00:04.220 align:middle line:84%
Now, so I claim that
absolute convergence

01:00:04.220 --> 01:00:06.000 align:middle line:90%
is stronger than convergence.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:16.740 align:middle line:90%


01:00:16.740 --> 01:00:32.288 align:middle line:84%
So absolute convergence
implies convergence.

01:00:32.288 --> 01:00:34.100 align:middle line:90%
So this is a theorem.

01:00:34.100 --> 01:00:38.420 align:middle line:90%


01:00:38.420 --> 01:00:40.860 align:middle line:84%
But it's not the
other way around.

01:00:40.860 --> 01:00:44.140 align:middle line:84%
So if you have
what's called the--

01:00:44.140 --> 01:00:46.980 align:middle line:90%
so here, an example.

01:00:46.980 --> 01:00:49.900 align:middle line:84%
And we haven't yet proved
that it's converging,

01:00:49.900 --> 01:00:52.050 align:middle line:84%
but we'll do that in
some later lecture.

01:00:52.050 --> 01:00:59.180 align:middle line:90%


01:00:59.180 --> 01:01:03.460 align:middle line:90%
So here's an example.

01:01:03.460 --> 01:01:07.140 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking at
the series minus 1

01:01:07.140 --> 01:01:11.300 align:middle line:84%
to the power n divided
by n, n equal to 1

01:01:11.300 --> 01:01:17.340 align:middle line:84%
to infinity, let's say you see
if this had just had been 1,

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:19.860 align:middle line:84%
then it had been
the harmonic series.

01:01:19.860 --> 01:01:25.280 align:middle line:84%
This here series is also
kind of like a famous series.

01:01:25.280 --> 01:01:29.590 align:middle line:84%
It's called the alternating
harmonic series.

01:01:29.590 --> 01:01:34.780 align:middle line:90%


01:01:34.780 --> 01:01:35.960 align:middle line:90%
And it's alternating.

01:01:35.960 --> 01:01:39.560 align:middle line:84%
Alternating means that the
sign of it is alternating.

01:01:39.560 --> 01:01:43.020 align:middle line:84%
So the sign of
this an element, it

01:01:43.020 --> 01:01:47.540 align:middle line:84%
keeps changing from a-- in this
case, the first one is negative.

01:01:47.540 --> 01:01:49.140 align:middle line:90%
The next one is positive.

01:01:49.140 --> 01:01:59.020 align:middle line:84%
So go back and forth between
around 0, so harmonic series.

01:01:59.020 --> 01:02:10.740 align:middle line:84%
And this series is convergent,
but not absolutely convergent,

01:02:10.740 --> 01:02:16.880 align:middle line:84%
because if you slap
absolute value sign,

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:18.160 align:middle line:90%
you get the harmonic series.

01:02:18.160 --> 01:02:21.260 align:middle line:84%
And we already know that this
is not convergent, but not

01:02:21.260 --> 01:02:22.520 align:middle line:90%
absolutely convergent.

01:02:22.520 --> 01:02:30.340 align:middle line:90%


01:02:30.340 --> 01:02:36.130 align:middle line:84%
So this is the alternating
harmonic series.

01:02:36.130 --> 01:02:41.710 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to prove that
absolute convergence implies

01:02:41.710 --> 01:02:42.690 align:middle line:90%
convergence.

01:02:42.690 --> 01:02:45.710 align:middle line:90%


01:02:45.710 --> 01:02:49.010 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm going to look
at-- so I take two series.

01:02:49.010 --> 01:02:50.790 align:middle line:90%
So I have sn.

01:02:50.790 --> 01:02:58.670 align:middle line:84%
That's my original series, ai,
i equal to 0, to n, like that.

01:02:58.670 --> 01:03:02.150 align:middle line:84%
And then I take the one where
I snap absolute value sign

01:03:02.150 --> 01:03:11.110 align:middle line:84%
and I denote it with a bar,
so i equal to 0 to n of ai.

01:03:11.110 --> 01:03:15.350 align:middle line:84%
And then I make a
little observation.

01:03:15.350 --> 01:03:21.550 align:middle line:84%
And the observation
is that if I take--

01:03:21.550 --> 01:03:28.790 align:middle line:84%
if I'm looking at
sn and sm, so just

01:03:28.790 --> 01:03:35.670 align:middle line:84%
think about m here
is larger than n,

01:03:35.670 --> 01:03:38.510 align:middle line:84%
then you can think
about this thing here,

01:03:38.510 --> 01:03:42.350 align:middle line:84%
as this thing here is
just where you're summing

01:03:42.350 --> 01:03:53.830 align:middle line:90%
from n plus 1 n up to an.

01:03:53.830 --> 01:03:57.070 align:middle line:90%
That's this difference, right?

01:03:57.070 --> 01:04:03.710 align:middle line:84%
But if you take absolute value
on this, absolute value on that,

01:04:03.710 --> 01:04:08.150 align:middle line:84%
well, that's of course
lesser or equal to where

01:04:08.150 --> 01:04:23.050 align:middle line:84%
you're taking absolute value on
each individual one, like that.

01:04:23.050 --> 01:04:29.110 align:middle line:90%
But this thing here is just--

01:04:29.110 --> 01:04:34.510 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is just for
the other series, this series.

01:04:34.510 --> 01:04:36.570 align:middle line:90%
It's the same difference.

01:04:36.570 --> 01:04:41.510 align:middle line:90%


01:04:41.510 --> 01:04:44.237 align:middle line:84%
And here, actually, I don't even
need to take absolute value,

01:04:44.237 --> 01:04:45.570 align:middle line:90%
but I could take absolute value.

01:04:45.570 --> 01:04:49.270 align:middle line:90%
But this is always [INAUDIBLE].

01:04:49.270 --> 01:04:51.830 align:middle line:90%
And so you see that--

01:04:51.830 --> 01:04:54.370 align:middle line:84%
so you make this
little observation.

01:04:54.370 --> 01:04:59.430 align:middle line:84%
But now we know that if it
is absolutely convergent,

01:04:59.430 --> 01:05:01.870 align:middle line:84%
then this sequence
here converge.

01:05:01.870 --> 01:05:04.310 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
in particular, it's

01:05:04.310 --> 01:05:07.630 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to saying that
it's a Cauchy sequence.

01:05:07.630 --> 01:05:11.510 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that since if
you are sufficiently far out,

01:05:11.510 --> 01:05:13.550 align:middle line:84%
these things have
bunched together,

01:05:13.550 --> 01:05:17.350 align:middle line:84%
epsilon together if you are
bigger than some capital N.

01:05:17.350 --> 01:05:20.070 align:middle line:84%
But now, this inequality
say that this thing here

01:05:20.070 --> 01:05:21.190 align:middle line:90%
bunch together.

01:05:21.190 --> 01:05:25.430 align:middle line:84%
So you see that if
this is convergent,

01:05:25.430 --> 01:05:28.270 align:middle line:90%
then it's a Cauchy sequence.

01:05:28.270 --> 01:05:31.050 align:middle line:84%
But this means that this
here is a Cauchy sequence.

01:05:31.050 --> 01:05:34.250 align:middle line:84%
So it means that the original
series was convergent.

01:05:34.250 --> 01:05:40.030 align:middle line:90%


01:05:40.030 --> 01:05:47.710 align:middle line:84%
And so now, let's look
at one more example.

01:05:47.710 --> 01:05:50.240 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll talk
about some of the tests.

01:05:50.240 --> 01:05:54.150 align:middle line:90%


01:05:54.150 --> 01:06:00.550 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at-- so we saw
that the harmonic series is

01:06:00.550 --> 01:06:01.490 align:middle line:90%
divergent.

01:06:01.490 --> 01:06:10.230 align:middle line:90%


01:06:10.230 --> 01:06:14.030 align:middle line:84%
So we saw that the harmonic
series is divergent.

01:06:14.030 --> 01:06:15.720 align:middle line:90%
But what about--

01:06:15.720 --> 01:06:20.350 align:middle line:90%


01:06:20.350 --> 01:06:22.090 align:middle line:90%
I mean, what about--

01:06:22.090 --> 01:06:25.450 align:middle line:84%
so there's another
thing you could do.

01:06:25.450 --> 01:06:30.670 align:middle line:84%
So maybe the most important
series is the geometric series.

01:06:30.670 --> 01:06:33.950 align:middle line:84%
After that, you can debate
a little bit which series

01:06:33.950 --> 01:06:35.790 align:middle line:90%
is the most important.

01:06:35.790 --> 01:06:40.270 align:middle line:84%
But this here is some
other candidates for that.

01:06:40.270 --> 01:06:49.350 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at now the sum
here, n equal to 0, to infinity.

01:06:49.350 --> 01:06:55.590 align:middle line:84%
And I'm looking at
1 over n squared.

01:06:55.590 --> 01:06:57.950 align:middle line:84%
But you could do it
more generally where

01:06:57.950 --> 01:06:59.790 align:middle line:90%
you raise it to some power.

01:06:59.790 --> 01:07:03.510 align:middle line:84%
If that power was 1,
you got the alternating.

01:07:03.510 --> 01:07:05.050 align:middle line:90%
You got the harmonic series.

01:07:05.050 --> 01:07:08.950 align:middle line:84%
But now I'm just looking
at a specific power, 2.

01:07:08.950 --> 01:07:11.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:11.350 --> 01:07:16.510 align:middle line:84%
And so I claim that this
series here, this here is--

01:07:16.510 --> 01:07:20.137 align:middle line:90%


01:07:20.137 --> 01:07:21.970 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this one doesn't
really have a name,

01:07:21.970 --> 01:07:24.430 align:middle line:90%
but it is a key series.

01:07:24.430 --> 01:07:27.850 align:middle line:84%
And so I claim that
this here is convergent.

01:07:27.850 --> 01:07:37.510 align:middle line:90%


01:07:37.510 --> 01:07:44.510 align:middle line:84%
Now, you observe that the an,
in this case, this is just 1

01:07:44.510 --> 01:07:46.470 align:middle line:90%
over n squared.

01:07:46.470 --> 01:07:48.750 align:middle line:90%
And these here are non-negative.

01:07:48.750 --> 01:07:52.050 align:middle line:84%
So all we need to do is--
so we just need to prove.

01:07:52.050 --> 01:07:55.170 align:middle line:84%
So when the a n's
are non-negative,

01:07:55.170 --> 01:07:59.750 align:middle line:84%
all you need to prove
is that the sequence--

01:07:59.750 --> 01:08:02.830 align:middle line:84%
you just need to
prove, need to show

01:08:02.830 --> 01:08:12.950 align:middle line:84%
that the sn, which is
where you're summing here,

01:08:12.950 --> 01:08:15.230 align:middle line:90%
i equal to--

01:08:15.230 --> 01:08:19.430 align:middle line:84%
or you can't, you shouldn't
sum from 0, sum from 1,

01:08:19.430 --> 01:08:23.560 align:middle line:90%
i equal to 1 to n--

01:08:23.560 --> 01:08:27.920 align:middle line:84%
that we will need to prove
that these here are bounded.

01:08:27.920 --> 01:08:31.899 align:middle line:84%
This is because the a
n's are non-negative.

01:08:31.899 --> 01:08:35.240 align:middle line:90%


01:08:35.240 --> 01:08:40.800 align:middle line:90%
So now the idea here is that--

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:48.000 align:middle line:84%
I mean, again, this is not
necessarily how I would do it.

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:53.120 align:middle line:84%
But the advantage with
this here is that it

01:08:53.120 --> 01:08:55.460 align:middle line:90%
doesn't use anything fancy.

01:08:55.460 --> 01:09:00.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's not like the
way later on you do it,

01:09:00.240 --> 01:09:01.899 align:middle line:90%
you will use the integral test.

01:09:01.899 --> 01:09:04.520 align:middle line:84%
But we haven't talked
about this integral test.

01:09:04.520 --> 01:09:08.000 align:middle line:84%
So you can do it
very simple minded.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:17.040 align:middle line:84%
And so the claim here is
that you want to compare.

01:09:17.040 --> 01:09:29.319 align:middle line:84%
So we want to make a foreign
claim that if you're looking

01:09:29.319 --> 01:09:33.600 align:middle line:90%
at s to the 2n plus 1--

01:09:33.600 --> 01:09:38.840 align:middle line:84%
sorry, to the 2n, so it's just
similar to what we did before.

01:09:38.840 --> 01:09:44.880 align:middle line:84%
If we want to prove that this
thing here for this series,

01:09:44.880 --> 01:09:54.800 align:middle line:84%
that this is less than the sum
here from i equal to 0 to n

01:09:54.800 --> 01:10:02.920 align:middle line:84%
of 1/2 to the power, i, so
we'll put n to n minus 1.

01:10:02.920 --> 01:10:06.320 align:middle line:90%
So we claim this thing here.

01:10:06.320 --> 01:10:08.640 align:middle line:90%
Now, you see that--

01:10:08.640 --> 01:10:13.680 align:middle line:84%
so we claim that we have
this inequality for all n.

01:10:13.680 --> 01:10:18.640 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here, we
already know that this here is

01:10:18.640 --> 01:10:29.380 align:middle line:84%
a geometric series with c equal
to 1/2, so it's convergent.

01:10:29.380 --> 01:10:33.440 align:middle line:90%


01:10:33.440 --> 01:10:37.600 align:middle line:84%
And you see this thing
here is a subsequence.

01:10:37.600 --> 01:10:41.080 align:middle line:84%
But it's a subsequence
because this is convergent.

01:10:41.080 --> 01:10:47.640 align:middle line:84%
This here is bounded
by something fixed.

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:52.280 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this
subsequent here is bounded.

01:10:52.280 --> 01:10:57.700 align:middle line:84%
But the original series was a
monotone increasing sequence.

01:10:57.700 --> 01:11:01.960 align:middle line:84%
So if a subsequence is bounded,
then the original sequence

01:11:01.960 --> 01:11:04.360 align:middle line:90%
is bounded and so convergent.

01:11:04.360 --> 01:11:06.120 align:middle line:90%
So we just need to prove--

01:11:06.120 --> 01:11:09.080 align:middle line:84%
we just need to give
a bound, like this.

01:11:09.080 --> 01:11:11.920 align:middle line:84%
And the bound here you get
is by we already determined

01:11:11.920 --> 01:11:18.160 align:middle line:84%
that this here is less than
or equal to 1 over 1 minus c.

01:11:18.160 --> 01:11:19.920 align:middle line:90%
c is 1/2.

01:11:19.920 --> 01:11:21.260 align:middle line:90%
So this is like this.

01:11:21.260 --> 01:11:23.680 align:middle line:90%
So this is 1/2.

01:11:23.680 --> 01:11:27.200 align:middle line:90%
So this whole thing here is 2.

01:11:27.200 --> 01:11:31.560 align:middle line:84%
So this here would be
bounded by 2, right?

01:11:31.560 --> 01:11:35.040 align:middle line:90%
So now we want to prove.

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:37.180 align:middle line:84%
So we want to prove
this claim here.

01:11:37.180 --> 01:11:42.260 align:middle line:84%
So if you can prove this claim,
then we have that the series,

01:11:42.260 --> 01:11:46.200 align:middle line:90%
this series here is convergent.

01:11:46.200 --> 01:11:47.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:47.720 --> 01:11:51.760 align:middle line:90%
So now let's try to do that.

01:11:51.760 --> 01:11:57.320 align:middle line:84%
So when n is equal to
1, so we do it again

01:11:57.320 --> 01:12:01.820 align:middle line:84%
in the same way, which
is called by induction.

01:12:01.820 --> 01:12:07.600 align:middle line:84%
We do it for, first of
all, for n equal to 1.

01:12:07.600 --> 01:12:13.660 align:middle line:84%
For n equal to 1, it
is a claim that s--

01:12:13.660 --> 01:12:16.860 align:middle line:84%
if n is equal to 1,
this is true, minus 1.

01:12:16.860 --> 01:12:17.840 align:middle line:90%
That's 1.

01:12:17.840 --> 01:12:23.740 align:middle line:84%
So it's a claim that this
thing here is bigger equals--

01:12:23.740 --> 01:12:26.160 align:middle line:90%
it's less than or equal to.

01:12:26.160 --> 01:12:30.480 align:middle line:84%
And now when n is
equal to 1, you're

01:12:30.480 --> 01:12:31.820 align:middle line:90%
just summing over one thing.

01:12:31.820 --> 01:12:33.040 align:middle line:90%
It's just one thing.

01:12:33.040 --> 01:12:36.340 align:middle line:90%
And it is 1/2 to the power 0.

01:12:36.340 --> 01:12:37.480 align:middle line:90%
And that's 1.

01:12:37.480 --> 01:12:41.300 align:middle line:84%
So for n equal to 1, this
is what we need to show.

01:12:41.300 --> 01:12:46.000 align:middle line:90%


01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:53.600 align:middle line:84%
But now, let's see
for n equal to 1,

01:12:53.600 --> 01:12:55.820 align:middle line:90%
well, this here is indeed 1.

01:12:55.820 --> 01:12:57.200 align:middle line:90%
So that's OK.

01:12:57.200 --> 01:12:59.900 align:middle line:90%
So this is OK.

01:12:59.900 --> 01:13:03.960 align:middle line:90%


01:13:03.960 --> 01:13:14.760 align:middle line:84%
So now assume that s to the
power 2n minus 1 is bounded

01:13:14.760 --> 01:13:23.880 align:middle line:84%
by this i equal to 0 to n
minus 1 of 1/2 to the power i.

01:13:23.880 --> 01:13:26.040 align:middle line:90%
So assume this.

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:31.500 align:middle line:84%
And we want to prove the
same thing, but for n plus 1,

01:13:31.500 --> 01:13:46.290 align:middle line:84%
so want to show the same
inequality for n plus 1.

01:13:46.290 --> 01:13:46.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:46.790 --> 01:13:50.480 align:middle line:90%


01:13:50.480 --> 01:13:51.860 align:middle line:90%
So let me do that.

01:13:51.860 --> 01:14:01.280 align:middle line:90%


01:14:01.280 --> 01:14:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at
s2n plus 1 minus 1.

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:14.200 align:middle line:84%
So s2n plus 1 minus 1 I can
write as where I'm summing

01:14:14.200 --> 01:14:18.850 align:middle line:90%
the first 2n minus 1.

01:14:18.850 --> 01:14:24.890 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm summing,
and then plus,

01:14:24.890 --> 01:14:38.090 align:middle line:84%
and then where I'm summing from
i equal to 2n to up to 2n plus 1

01:14:38.090 --> 01:14:40.130 align:middle line:90%
minus 1.

01:14:40.130 --> 01:14:44.650 align:middle line:90%
And then it's 1 over i squared.

01:14:44.650 --> 01:14:49.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, in this case,
remember before we

01:14:49.170 --> 01:14:52.010 align:middle line:84%
wanted to prove that
something was divergent.

01:14:52.010 --> 01:14:54.110 align:middle line:84%
So we wanted to
give a lower bound.

01:14:54.110 --> 01:14:56.570 align:middle line:84%
In this case, we want
to give an upper bound.

01:14:56.570 --> 01:15:01.712 align:middle line:84%
So when we do this, we
think about what is the--

01:15:01.712 --> 01:15:03.170 align:middle line:84%
instead of what is
the smallest, we

01:15:03.170 --> 01:15:06.290 align:middle line:84%
think about what is the
largest of these numbers.

01:15:06.290 --> 01:15:09.210 align:middle line:90%
But that's the first one.

01:15:09.210 --> 01:15:11.790 align:middle line:84%
And there are, again,
just like before,

01:15:11.790 --> 01:15:14.170 align:middle line:90%
there are 2n many of them.

01:15:14.170 --> 01:15:20.210 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is less
than or equal to s2n minus 1.

01:15:20.210 --> 01:15:22.610 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, like this.

01:15:22.610 --> 01:15:24.950 align:middle line:90%
And then there are 2n many.

01:15:24.950 --> 01:15:26.070 align:middle line:90%
They're all non-negative.

01:15:26.070 --> 01:15:34.490 align:middle line:84%
And the first one is the
largest, so 1 over 2n squared,

01:15:34.490 --> 01:15:38.530 align:middle line:90%
like this, right.

01:15:38.530 --> 01:15:41.870 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
this thing here is--

01:15:41.870 --> 01:15:45.490 align:middle line:84%
so now we can fill
in the assumption.

01:15:45.490 --> 01:15:50.770 align:middle line:84%
We are assuming that this
here was less than this.

01:15:50.770 --> 01:16:00.110 align:middle line:84%
This is sum from i equal to 0 to
n minus 1 of 1/2 to the power i.

01:16:00.110 --> 01:16:05.210 align:middle line:90%


01:16:05.210 --> 01:16:11.210 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, but
the square kills that one

01:16:11.210 --> 01:16:15.050 align:middle line:84%
and you're still
left with 1 over 2n.

01:16:15.050 --> 01:16:19.250 align:middle line:84%
But you see, this is, of
course, exactly the next one

01:16:19.250 --> 01:16:20.150 align:middle line:90%
in the series.

01:16:20.150 --> 01:16:29.970 align:middle line:84%
So this is i equal to 0 to n
of 1/2 to the power i, again.

01:16:29.970 --> 01:16:34.242 align:middle line:84%
And that's, indeed, this is
like the induction step, right?

01:16:34.242 --> 01:16:35.950 align:middle line:84%
This is what's called
the induction step.

01:16:35.950 --> 01:16:38.530 align:middle line:90%
So it's true also.

01:16:38.530 --> 01:16:41.110 align:middle line:84%
So if it's true
for n, the claim,

01:16:41.110 --> 01:16:43.150 align:middle line:84%
then it's also
true for n plus 1.

01:16:43.150 --> 01:16:52.570 align:middle line:90%


01:16:52.570 --> 01:16:54.450 align:middle line:90%
So now let me--

01:16:54.450 --> 01:16:55.750 align:middle line:90%
I have just four minutes left.

01:16:55.750 --> 01:16:58.370 align:middle line:84%
There's a little bit
more, and I already

01:16:58.370 --> 01:17:01.010 align:middle line:90%
posted the lecture notes.

01:17:01.010 --> 01:17:05.340 align:middle line:84%
And there's a bit more
here I want to talk about.

01:17:05.340 --> 01:17:07.970 align:middle line:90%


01:17:07.970 --> 01:17:10.710 align:middle line:84%
So I want to talk about
some of the tests.

01:17:10.710 --> 01:17:14.650 align:middle line:84%
But we'll talk about that
more next time, also.

01:17:14.650 --> 01:17:33.130 align:middle line:84%
So to determine whether or not a
series is convergent, converge,

01:17:33.130 --> 01:17:37.140 align:middle line:84%
then there are a
number of tests.

01:17:37.140 --> 01:17:43.330 align:middle line:90%


01:17:43.330 --> 01:17:50.250 align:middle line:84%
And then of course, the key
point is to use the right test.

01:17:50.250 --> 01:17:52.910 align:middle line:90%
So I will just talk about--

01:17:52.910 --> 01:17:54.590 align:middle line:84%
so I just mentioned
some of the tests.

01:17:54.590 --> 01:17:57.550 align:middle line:84%
But we won't anyway go
through all of them now.

01:17:57.550 --> 01:17:59.910 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I can't go
through any of them.

01:17:59.910 --> 01:18:01.120 align:middle line:90%
So there's a comparison test.

01:18:01.120 --> 01:18:05.170 align:middle line:90%


01:18:05.170 --> 01:18:06.840 align:middle line:90%
There's a ratio test.

01:18:06.840 --> 01:18:10.730 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.730 --> 01:18:11.540 align:middle line:90%
There's root test.

01:18:11.540 --> 01:18:14.530 align:middle line:90%


01:18:14.530 --> 01:18:17.370 align:middle line:84%
And there's also the one I
talked about several times,

01:18:17.370 --> 01:18:18.220 align:middle line:90%
the integral test.

01:18:18.220 --> 01:18:21.370 align:middle line:90%


01:18:21.370 --> 01:18:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And then there's even one called
the alternate series test.

01:18:24.740 --> 01:18:34.450 align:middle line:90%


01:18:34.450 --> 01:18:39.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, maybe I can just talk
about the comparison test.

01:18:39.310 --> 01:18:41.110 align:middle line:84%
That's, in a way,
the simplest of them.

01:18:41.110 --> 01:18:44.210 align:middle line:90%


01:18:44.210 --> 01:18:50.730 align:middle line:84%
And so the comparison test is
that you're looking at two.

01:18:50.730 --> 01:18:52.630 align:middle line:84%
So you have these
two series here.

01:18:52.630 --> 01:18:55.250 align:middle line:90%


01:18:55.250 --> 01:18:57.070 align:middle line:84%
And you have this
other series here.

01:18:57.070 --> 01:19:03.290 align:middle line:90%


01:19:03.290 --> 01:19:10.070 align:middle line:84%
And the comparison tests say
that if you have an equal to 0,

01:19:10.070 --> 01:19:12.290 align:middle line:90%
lesser equal to bn--

01:19:12.290 --> 01:19:22.330 align:middle line:84%
so if you have this end,
and this here is here,

01:19:22.330 --> 01:19:32.770 align:middle line:84%
converge, then the
corresponding thing with an

01:19:32.770 --> 01:19:33.760 align:middle line:90%
will also converge.

01:19:33.760 --> 01:19:40.810 align:middle line:90%


01:19:40.810 --> 01:19:46.010 align:middle line:84%
And this is the simplest
version of the comparison test.

01:19:46.010 --> 01:19:49.930 align:middle line:84%
And this is, in a
way, used in two ways.

01:19:49.930 --> 01:19:52.650 align:middle line:90%
So often you have a series.

01:19:52.650 --> 01:19:56.530 align:middle line:84%
And maybe it could be a
super complicated series.

01:19:56.530 --> 01:20:00.010 align:middle line:84%
And but you see
some kind of path.

01:20:00.010 --> 01:20:04.250 align:middle line:84%
And so you can compare it
with a much simpler series

01:20:04.250 --> 01:20:07.280 align:middle line:84%
that perhaps you already
know whether it's converging.

01:20:07.280 --> 01:20:11.660 align:middle line:84%
And so if you can compare
it with something else

01:20:11.660 --> 01:20:15.100 align:middle line:84%
and you know that that
converge, then you

01:20:15.100 --> 01:20:19.020 align:middle line:84%
conclude that the an
series is convergent.

01:20:19.020 --> 01:20:22.100 align:middle line:84%
It's also sometimes
used that you

01:20:22.100 --> 01:20:25.620 align:middle line:84%
want to determine whether
this series is convergent.

01:20:25.620 --> 01:20:29.180 align:middle line:84%
But actually, you
can easily compare it

01:20:29.180 --> 01:20:32.960 align:middle line:84%
with some other series where
you have this relationship here,

01:20:32.960 --> 01:20:36.340 align:middle line:84%
and this one you already
know is divergent.

01:20:36.340 --> 01:20:38.540 align:middle line:90%
So it's used in both ways.

01:20:38.540 --> 01:20:42.320 align:middle line:84%
It's used to both determine
that a series is convergent.

01:20:42.320 --> 01:20:45.320 align:middle line:84%
And it's also used to determine
that the series is divergent.

01:20:45.320 --> 01:20:48.620 align:middle line:84%
So there's a little
bit more about tests

01:20:48.620 --> 01:20:51.660 align:middle line:90%
in the lecture notes.

01:20:51.660 --> 01:20:53.800 align:middle line:84%
But we will, anyway, talk
about it more next time.

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:54.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:20:54.220 --> 01:20:56.178 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about the intuition

01:20:56.178 --> 01:20:58.108 align:middle line:90%
of this [INAUDIBLE].

01:20:58.108 --> 01:21:02.523 align:middle line:90%


01:21:02.523 --> 01:21:03.440 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

01:21:03.440 --> 01:21:05.240 align:middle line:90%
So that's right.

01:21:05.240 --> 01:21:12.380 align:middle line:90%
So that sort of thing is--

01:21:12.380 --> 01:21:17.820 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this last one shows
you that the geometric series

01:21:17.820 --> 01:21:23.640 align:middle line:84%
is one that come up often as a
kind of comparison, in a way.

01:21:23.640 --> 01:21:28.320 align:middle line:84%
How you get it is different
for different people.

01:21:28.320 --> 01:21:30.300 align:middle line:84%
Obviously you don't
start with the claim.

01:21:30.300 --> 01:21:32.660 align:middle line:84%
You're looking at
the first few things

01:21:32.660 --> 01:21:34.600 align:middle line:84%
and you see a
pattern, basically.

01:21:34.600 --> 01:21:35.780 align:middle line:90%
But it's not--

01:21:35.780 --> 01:21:39.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is not the
way you want to really--

01:21:39.220 --> 01:21:44.540 align:middle line:84%
later on, I would never
prove any kind of convergence

01:21:44.540 --> 01:21:45.700 align:middle line:90%
like this.

01:21:45.700 --> 01:21:51.460 align:middle line:84%
There's a way of
comparing it with the--

01:21:51.460 --> 01:21:53.620 align:middle line:84%
so the idea is, let
me just tell you.

01:21:53.620 --> 01:21:57.540 align:middle line:84%
But of course, the
lecture is over.

01:21:57.540 --> 01:22:01.880 align:middle line:84%
So the integral test is
that you're looking at--

01:22:01.880 --> 01:22:03.720 align:middle line:90%
so you're looking at a series.

01:22:03.720 --> 01:22:06.940 align:middle line:84%
And if you have a series
of non-negative numbers,

01:22:06.940 --> 01:22:12.900 align:middle line:84%
you can think about that the
series is like the area below.

01:22:12.900 --> 01:22:19.660 align:middle line:84%
If you think about this here
as a1, and this is maybe a2,

01:22:19.660 --> 01:22:24.060 align:middle line:84%
then you can think about the
sum as the sum of the areas,

01:22:24.060 --> 01:22:25.300 align:middle line:90%
like this.

01:22:25.300 --> 01:22:28.980 align:middle line:84%
And so the integral of testers
that you're comparing it

01:22:28.980 --> 01:22:34.020 align:middle line:84%
with some curve and the area
that lies below it, then it's

01:22:34.020 --> 01:22:35.540 align:middle line:90%
much more clear.

01:22:35.540 --> 01:22:39.380 align:middle line:84%
The other one is like where
you have to do it case by case.

01:22:39.380 --> 01:22:42.640 align:middle line:84%
Here there's a kind
of general idea.

01:22:42.640 --> 01:22:45.958 align:middle line:84%
So it's nice, in
this particular case.

01:22:45.958 --> 01:22:46.500 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure.

01:22:46.500 --> 01:22:47.360 align:middle line:90%
You know what I mean?

01:22:47.360 --> 01:22:49.360 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you have to look
at the first few things

01:22:49.360 --> 01:22:50.840 align:middle line:90%
and see if you see a pattern.

01:22:50.840 --> 01:22:53.240 align:middle line:84%
And of course, you don't
start with a claim.

01:22:53.240 --> 01:22:56.900 align:middle line:84%
That's like the end, when
you actually have a claim,

01:22:56.900 --> 01:23:00.090 align:middle line:84%
then you already
know what's going on.

01:23:00.090 --> 01:23:03.000 align:middle line:90%